## Step 10: Potential Pitfalls and How to Avoid Them

### Pitfall 1: `creating` vs `created`
Using `creating` for the `created` event log would result in `loggable_id` being null because the auto-increment ID is not assigned until after the INSERT. The plan uses `created` (past tense) hook to guarantee `$model->id` is set.

### Pitfall 2: Infinite loop risk (not present but worth documenting)
`ActivityLog::create()` inside the trait hooks into `ActivityLog`'s own `creating`/`created` events. Since `ActivityLog` does NOT use `LogsActivity`, there is no recursion. Never add `use LogsActivity` to `ActivityLog` itself.

### Pitfall 3: The `reorder` controller bypasses dirty tracking safely
`TaskController@reorder` calls `$task->update(['position' => ..., 'status' => ...])`. Status IS in `$loggableAttributes`. This means if `reorder` changes status along with position, the status change WILL be logged. Looking at the controller code, `reorder` only updates `position` and preserves the existing `status` (it sends the current status back from the frontend), so in practice it will log a no-op for status if status didn't actually change — but `getDirty()` only returns truly changed values, so if status is the same, it won't appear in `getDirty()` and no log entry will be written. Confirmed safe.

### Pitfall 4: `updateStatus` correctly logs status changes
`TaskController@updateStatus` calls `$task->update(['status' => ..., 'position' => ...])`. `position` is not in `$loggableAttributes`, so it is filtered out. `status` IS in `$loggableAttributes` and if it changed, it WILL be logged. This is correct expected behavior — dragging a card across columns should appear in the log.

### Pitfall 5: SQLite and JSON columns
SQLite does not have a native JSON type but stores it as TEXT. Laravel's `'array'` cast handles serialization/deserialization transparently. The `json()` column definition in migrations will work fine with SQLite.

### Pitfall 6: Alpine.js `x-for` on object keys
The log entries display `entry.new_values` by iterating with `x-for="(val, field) in entry.new_values"`. Alpine.js 3.x supports iterating over object entries with this syntax. Since `new_values` is an object (JSON decoded), this works correctly. Verify the `ActivityLog` model's `'array'` cast is in place — without it, `new_values` would arrive as a string and Alpine would iterate over characters.

